s on every aspect of American life, from the labor force to social welfare programs to tax revenue. What emerges is a critical, utterly complete examination of what non-native Americans bring to the country, including immigration’s tendency to elevate the wages and skills of those who are native-born. News coverage has prompted many to question the humanity of American immigration policies; The Border Within opens a conversation of whether it is effective. The United States spends billions each year on detention and deportation, all without economic gain and at a great human cost. With depth and discipline, the authors dissect the shock-and-awe policies that make up a broken, often cruel system, while illuminating the lives caught in the chaos. It is an essential work with far-reaching implications for immigrants and non-immigrants alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aIllegal immigrationzUnited States. 0aImmigration enforcementxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aNoncitizenszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aice, capitalism, border, patrol, economic, immigration, customs, enforcement, mexican, history, borders, latin, american, undocumented, central, migrant, farm, workers, nafta, illegal, trump, asylum, law, policy, reform, detention, deportation.1 aThompson, Kalee, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226270364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226270364/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles